"# Final Project Specification\n\nThis document is the final, consensus engineering blueprint for the single-user, client-only todo SPA. It reconciles the original specification with the Architecture, Security, and QA reviews and prioritizes (in order): production reliability, security, maintainability, then developer experience.\n\nWhere reviewers identified gaps or risks, this specification authoritatively defines expected behavior, APIs, failure modes, and QA/testing requirements to ensure a robust, secure, and maintainable MVP.\n\n---\n\n## Project Overview\n\nA lightweight, single-user todo-list SPA for personal use. Core goals remain:\n\n- Minimal feature surface for personal task tracking (CRUD tasks, projects/lists).\n- Local-only persistence in the browser (IndexedDB preferred; well-defined fallback).\n- Small, maintainable TypeScript React codebase suitable for static hosting.\n- Fast, offline-capable experience.\n\nNew/clarified high-level additions driven by reviews:\n\n- User-accessible import/export (JSON) and explicit backup guidance.\n- Cross-tab synchronization (BroadcastChannel with storage fallback).\n- DB versioning and migration policies.\n- Robust IndexedDB availability and quota failure handling.\n- Safe project-deletion semantics with confirmation and undo.\n- Optional local encryption for users requiring extra privacy.\n\n---\n\n## Final Architecture Decisions\n\nHigh-level architecture remains client-only SPA. Key decisions and rationale:\n\n- State management: use a small, selector-friendly store (Zustand) for global task state to avoid broad React Context re-renders. Keep UI preferences in React Context if needed. Rationale: better performance with large lists and localized subscriptions.\n- Storage: IndexedDB via a small idb-based adapter as primary persistent store. Implement explicit detection, migration, and graceful fallback to a limited localStorage mode or in-memory store only when necessary (see Storage Adapter). Prefer IndexedDB always for full-data persistence.\n- Cross-tab sync: BroadcastChannel for same-origin tabs; fallback to window.storage events where BroadcastChannel is unavailable.\n- Offline load of static assets: optional service worker (small Workbox-based caching) to enable app load offline after first visit. Keep SW simple and ensure safe update flow.\n- Optimistic UI: enabled for snappy interactions; every optimistic update must define rollback behavior in case persistence fails.\n- Data portability: add explicit Export (download JSON) and Import (upload JSON) UI/flow. Include version metadata to support migrations.\n- Security hardening: enforce safe rendering of all user input as plain text; schema validation in service layer; CSP guidance and CI security checks.\n\nComponent responsibilities (concise):\n\n- UI Layer: TaskListView, TaskItem, TaskEditor (modal/drawer), ProjectManager, Header, Settings, Toast/Undo manager.\n- State Layer: Zustand store for tasks/projects + selectors; local UI state in components.\n- Service Layer: TaskService, ProjectService (application logic, validation, optimistic update helpers).\n- Storage Adapter: idb abstraction with open/transaction/migrate routines + event emission.\n- Cross-Tab Sync Layer: BroadcastChannel wrapper producing idempotent mutation events.\n- Backup/Import/Export: JSON import/export utilities with validation and conflict handling.\n\nProduction reliability measures:\n\n- DB migration handlers with safe rollback and pre-migration export option.\n- Quota and failure detection with user-visible remediation guidance.\n- Cross-tab eventing to avoid stale UI.\n- Undo affordances for destructive actions and confirmation for project deletes.\n\n---\n\n## Technology Stack\n\nFrontend\n\n- Framework: React (>=17) + TypeScript.\n- State: Zustand (primary global store) + small React Context for UI prefs.\n- Bundler/Dev: Vite.\n- Storage: idb (tiny wrapper) for IndexedDB operations; a thin adapter layer to encapsulate logic and fallback.\n- Styling: Tailwind CSS (JIT) or CSS Modules — prefer Tailwind with purge/JIT to keep bundle small. Keep UI minimal.\n- UUID: uuid (v4) or equivalent deterministic UUID generator.\n- Schema validation: zod (runtime validation/whitelisting) for Service inputs/outputs.\n- Testing: Jest + React Testing Library (unit) and Playwright (recommended) or Cypress (E2E). Include fake-indexeddb for Node tests.\n- Optional libs: DOMPurify only if rich text allowed in the future; otherwise do not include.\n\nBuild & Deploy\n\n- Static hosting: Vercel/Netlify/GitHub Pages (documented in README).\n- CI: GitHub Actions:\n  - Lint, unit tests, coverage thresholds, build.\n  - Security checks: npm audit (or Snyk), dependency pin/lockfile verification, bundle-size check.\n  - E2E test matrix (Playwright) on merge to main before final deploy.\n  - Deploy step using secrets in GitHub Actions Secrets (never commit secrets).\n- Bundle size: enforce CI check; target < 1 MB production bundle (minimize dependencies, tree-shake, Tailwind purge).\n\n---\n\n## Database Design\n\nDB name: todo-app\nInitial version: 1 (with explicit migration framework)\n\nObject stores and schema (versioned; all timestamps are ISO 8601 strings):\n\n1. projects (keyPath: id)\n   - id: string (UUID v4)\n   - name: string\n   - createdAt: string\n   - updatedAt: string\n   - meta?: { color?: string } (optional future field)\n   - index: name\n\n2. tasks (keyPath: id)\n   - id: string (UUID v4)\n   - title: string (required)\n   - description?: string (plain text only)\n   - completed: boolean (default false)\n   - dueDate?: string | null (ISO timestamp) — store in UTC normalized ISO 8601\n   - projectId?: string | null\n   - position?: number (see ordering semantics)\n   - createdAt: string\n   - updatedAt: string\n   - indexes: projectId, completed, dueDate\n\nPosition / ordering semantics:\n- Use numeric positions (floating-point numbers) to represent order within a project.\n- When inserting between items, compute position as average of neighbors (e.g., (posA + posB)/2). If positions become too close (loss of precision), perform rebalance that rewrites positions for that project (e.g., resequence using integers with step = 1000) within a single IndexedDB transaction.\n- Persist position updates in the same transaction that updates moved tasks to keep ordering consistent.\n\nDB migration/versioning policy:\n- Use idb/openDB with an explicit upgrade handler mapping version→migration step functions.\n- Each migration step should:\n  - Validate existing data shape.\n  - Optionally export a pre-migration snapshot (in-memory) and surface to the user on error.\n  - Perform in-place transforms within onupgradeneeded transaction if possible; otherwise mark migration failure and preserve DB for manual recovery.\n- Maintain unit/integration tests that run migrations from previous versions.\n- Surface migration status and errors to the user and support manual export/import recovery.\n\nStorage Adapter responsibilities:\n- Feature-detect IndexedDB and graceful handling for environments where it's unsupported or throws (e.g., Safari private browsing).\n- Provide a consistent, Promise-based API:\n  - openDB(): Promise<void>\n  - get(store: 'tasks'|'projects', key: string): Promise<any|null>\n  - put(store: 'tasks'|'projects', value: any): Promise<any>\n  - delete(store: 'tasks'|'projects', key: string): Promise<void>\n  - getAll(store: 'tasks'|'projects', query?: any, direction?: any): Promise<any[]>\n  - transaction(stores: string[], mode: 'readonly'|'readwrite', fn: (tx) => Promise<void>): Promise<void>\n- Error handling: throw typed errors (e.g., StorageUnavailableError, QuotaExceededError, MigrationError). UI must display user-friendly messages.\n- Fallback: if IndexedDB fails to open or quota prevents writes:\n  - If in-memory fallback used: inform user export immediate (data not persisted across refresh).\n  - LocalStorage fallback allowed only as last resort with explicit UI warning; if used, store minimal dataset or encrypted payload (if user opted-in encryption). Prefer to avoid storing full dataset in localStorage unless user explicitly consents.\n- Observability: expose onChange subscriptions and emit events (local events) when stores change. See Cross-tab Sync.\n\nCross-store atomicity:\n- For operations involving both tasks and projects (e.g., project deletion + task updates), perform one IndexedDB transaction across stores to ensure consistency. If using fallback storage where transactions are not available, surface a clear warning and require user confirmation.\n\nData export/import and backup:\n- UI actions: Export Data (download JSON with version metadata), Import Data (user uploads JSON, schema validated via zod; if version mismatch, run migrations or prompt user).\n- Periodic local snapshot: optional in Settings (user-triggered or opt-in periodic export), do not auto-upload anywhere.\n- Document data permanence and caveats clearly in Settings and README (browser sync/backups caveat).\n\nCross-browser quirks and testing:\n- Test persistence and constructor behavior in Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit (Playwright test matrix).\n- Use fake-indexeddb for Node unit tests.\n\n---\n\n## Security Requirements\n\nSecurity is elevated relative to the original spec. Requirements below are mandatory for MVP.\n\n1. XSS / safe rendering\n   - Treat all user content as untrusted.\n   - Always render title, description, project names as escaped plain text (never innerHTML).\n   - If rich text introduced later, use a vetted sanitizer (DOMPurify) with a strict allowlist.\n   - Add unit/E2E tests asserting script payloads are escaped and do not execute.\n\n2. Input validation and prototype safety\n   - Validate all inputs at the Service layer using zod or equivalent.\n   - Whitelist accepted fields for create/update operations; disallow __proto__, constructor, prototype contamination keys.\n   - Use safe merges (explicit property assignment) rather than deep/naive merges.\n\n3. Local encryption (optional, opt-in)\n   - Provide an optional feature to encrypt user data at rest using Web Crypto API with a user-supplied passphrase (never stored).\n   - Derive key with PBKDF2 (configurable iterations) or scrypt/Argon2 via vetted libs if available.\n   - Use AES-GCM for encryption; explain caveats: lost password → unrecoverable data; browser sync/backup implications.\n   - Encryption is opt-in; default remains unencrypted storage.\n\n4. Fallback storage handling\n   - Prefer IndexedDB. If falling back to localStorage, minimize what is stored there and clearly warn the user.\n   - If localStorage used and user has opted to encrypt locally, store encrypted payloads only.\n\n5. CSP and hosting headers\n   - Require serving via HTTPS.\n   - Recommend strict Content-Security-Policy (no inline scripts/styles) for production hosting. Example policies should be documented in README and deploy docs. Use nonces or hashes for any needed inline code.\n   - Add other helpful headers: X-Frame-Options: DENY (or CSP frame-ancestors), Referrer-Policy: no-referrer-when-downgrade (or stricter), Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS), Permissions-Policy as appropriate.\n\n6. Dependency/supply-chain hygiene\n   - Pin dependency versions and commit lockfile.\n   - Enable Dependabot or Renovate and CI npm audit checks.\n   - CI should fail on critical/high vulnerabilities unless explicitly reviewed.\n\n7. CI secrets handling\n   - Store deploy tokens only in GitHub Actions Secrets and restrict access.\n   - Do not print secrets to logs.\n   - Add scanning for secrets in commits during PRs.\n\n8. Service Worker safety\n   - If SW used, keep logic minimal. Ensure index.html is served with short TTL and assets are content-hashed.\n   - Test SW update flow to avoid serving stale/malicious assets across deployments.\n\n9. Privacy disclosure\n   - Document in Settings/README that data is local to the browser profile but may be synced/backed up by browser or OS; offer guidance and the optional encryption feature. Warn if profile sync detected (if possible) and surface a warning.\n\n10. Error message hygiene\n   - Surface user-friendly error messages; do not expose stack traces or internal DB details to end users.\n\n---\n\n## API Design\n\nThe application exposes well-defined client-side services (no HTTP API). All functions are Promise-based and perform validation, safe merging, and emit change events (local and cross-tab).\n\nError model: service functions throw Error subclasses (e.g., ValidationError, NotFoundError, StorageUnavailableError, QuotaExceededError). UI should map these to friendly messages.\n\nTaskService\n- createTask(payload: { title: string; description?: string; dueDate?: string | null; projectId?: string | null; position?: number }): Promise<Task>\n  - Validates title (non-empty, max length), projectId exists or null.\n  - Assigns id, createdAt, updatedAt.\n  - Emits local onChange and cross-tab mutation event.\n- getTask(id: string): Promise<Task | null>\n- listTasks(filter?: { projectId?: string | null; completed?: boolean | 'all'; search?: string; sortBy?: 'createdAt' | 'dueDate' | 'position'; limit?: number; offset?: number }): Promise<Task[]>\n  - Search semantics: case-insensitive substring on title and description.\n  - Use virtualized rendering; implement pagination if list > 2000 items or via lazy fetch.\n- updateTask(id: string, updates: Partial<{ title:string; description:string|null; dueDate:string|null; projectId:string|null; position:number; completed:boolean }>): Promise<Task>\n  - Whitelisted fields only; validate types. Handle reassigning projectId (validate target project exists or null).\n  - Update updatedAt.\n  - Atomic for multi-entity changes when needed.\n- deleteTask(id: string): Promise<void>\n  - Support optimistic UI + undo window; physically delete after undo window expires.\n- toggleComplete(id: string): Promise<Task>\n  - Convenience wrapper that updates completed and updatedAt.\n- reorderTasks(projectId: string | null, orderedTaskIds: string[]): Promise<void>\n  - Computes/assigns positions in a transaction; rebalance if needed.\n\nProjectService\n- createProject(payload: { name: string }): Promise<Project>\n- getProject(id: string): Promise<Project | null>\n- listProjects(): Promise<Project[]>\n- updateProject(id: string, updates: Partial<{ name: string }>): Promise<Project>\n- deleteProject(id: string, options?: { strategy?: 'unassign' | 'cascade' | 'prompt'; allowUndo?: boolean }): Promise<void>\n  - Default strategy: 'unassign' (set projectId=null for tasks in a single transaction), require explicit confirmation UI and a toast Undo.\n  - For 'cascade' option, UI must require explicit confirmation and show count of tasks that will be removed and offer undo.\n  - Deletion must be atomic (transaction across projects + tasks) where possible.\n\nStorage Adapter API (abstraction; signatures representative)\n- openDB(): Promise<void>\n- get(store: 'tasks'|'projects', key: string): Promise<any|null>\n- put(store: string, value: any): Promise<any>\n- delete(store: string, key: string): Promise<void>\n- getAll(store: string, query?: any, direction?: any): Promise<any[]>\n- transaction(stores: string[], mode: 'readonly'|'readwrite', cb: (tx) => Promise<void>): Promise<void>\n- onChange(callback: (change: StorageChangeEvent) => void): Unsubscribe\n  - StorageChangeEvent includes { type: 'create'|'update'|'delete'|'migrate', store: string, ids?: string[], timestamp: string, sourceId?: string }\n- exportAll(): Promise<{ version:number; projects:Project[]; tasks:Task[] }>\n- importAll(payload: any): Promise<void> (validates and runs migrations if needed)\n\nCross-tab sync events\n- Use BroadcastChannel with message envelope:\n  - { sourceId: string (UUID for origin tab), opId: string (UUID), op: 'create'|'update'|'delete'|'reorder'|'migrate', store: 'tasks'|'projects', payload: { ids?: string[], entity?: any, changes?: any }, ts: string }\n- Receiver ignores messages from same sourceId or messages older than last applied timestamp. Messages must be applied idempotently and trigger UI invalidation (store refresh or selective updates).\n\nOptimistic update contract\n- Services should provide optimistic update hooks:\n  - Apply optimistic update to Zustand store immediately.\n  - Persist operation to Storage Adapter.\n  - On success: confirm and emit change.\n  - On failure: rollback to prior known state and surface error toast with retry option.\n- Tests must verify rollback behavior for failure scenarios (simulated QuotaExceededError).\n\nImport/Export contract\n- Export JSON includes version metadata and structural integrity signature (e.g., a simple manifest with counts and checksum of records).\n- Import validates schema using zod; if version mismatch, run migration or prompt user.\n\nData validation\n- Use zod schemas for Task and Project runtime validation.\n- Reject invalid projectId or invalid date formats.\n\nEventing & Observability\n- Expose store subscription hooks for UI and testing.\n- Optional developer-only diagnostics page (not shipped by default) to inspect DB state and errors (behind a feature flag).\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\nGoals: ensure reliability, cross-browser correctness, security (XSS), and user-facing behavior (undo, import/export, multi-tab).\n\nUnit tests (Jest + React Testing Library)\n- Services (TaskService/ProjectService) coverage target >= 90%.\n- Storage Adapter tests with fake-indexeddb: openDB, migrations, transaction semantics, error paths.\n- Input validation tests for zod schemas and prototype-pollution attempts.\n- Component unit tests: TaskItem, TaskEditor, ProjectManager, Header — target >= 75% for components.\n- Tests for optimistic updates and rollback behavior.\n\nIntegration tests\n- Tests for storage adapter + services together, including project deletion behaviors and position rebalancing.\n- Migration unit tests: simulate older DB versions and validate transformations.\n\nE2E tests (Playwright recommended; Cypress acceptable)\n- Test matrix: Chromium (desktop), Firefox (desktop), WebKit (macOS/Safari) — run at least on PR/merge to main.\n- Viewports: Desktop + Tablet + one Mobile breakpoint.\n- Scenarios:\n  - Full CRUD flow for tasks and projects; persistence across reload and browser restart simulation.\n  - Export/import round-trip and version migration.\n  - Project deletion (unassign and cascade options) with confirmation and undo behavior.\n  - Reordering tasks and position rebalancing.\n  - Cross-tab behavior: open two contexts; apply updates in one and assert propagation to the other.\n  - Quota/IndexedDB failure simulation: verify fallback and UI messaging.\n  - Service worker caching test: initial load, offline load after cache, update behavior.\n  - XSS attack vectors: attempt to input scripts into title/description and assert no execution; assert content is escaped.\n\nAccessibility testing\n- Automated axe checks in CI for main pages/components.\n- Manual verification tasks for:\n  - Keyboard-only flows for add/edit/toggle/delete with focus management.\n  - ARIA roles for dialogs, list semantics.\n  - Contrast ratios for UI colors; enforce minimum WCAG AA where applicable.\n- Accessibility coverage target for key flows (add/edit complete/delete) as automated tests + manual checklist.\n\nPerformance and load\n- Synthetic tests with ~5k tasks dataset to validate responsiveness and list virtualization.\n- CI bundle-size check (fail if > 1 MB target or configured threshold).\n\nSecurity tests in CI\n- npm audit (or Snyk) job.\n- Tests that verify CSP-compliant assets (no inline script/style), and SRI for any external resources (if used).\n- Tests for prototype pollution attempts in service APIs.\n\nQuality gates in CI\n- Linting must pass.\n- Unit tests must pass with coverage floor per module as above.\n- E2E test group runs on merge to main. Optionally run E2E in PRs for changed UI areas.\n- Security scan must pass (no critical/high vulnerabilities unreviewed).\n- Bundle-size check must pass.\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\nCore acceptance criteria from the original spec, expanded:\n\n1. Task CRUD\n   - Create a task with a title; view, edit, and delete it. Edits persist across reloads and restarts.\n   - UI updates optimistically; failed persistence triggers rollback and user notification.\n\n2. Project management\n   - Create, rename, delete projects.\n   - Default deletion behavior: unassign tasks (projectId → null) with explicit confirmation and an Undo toast. A cascade-delete option is available only with explicit confirm and shows affected count.\n   - Tasks can be assigned to a project; tasks referencing non-existent projects are detected and normalized to null on load/import.\n\n3. Persistence & storage resilience\n   - Data persists using IndexedDB across reloads and restarts where supported.\n   - The app detects IndexedDB unavailability/quota errors and falls back gracefully, informing the user and offering export.\n   - Import/Export (JSON) is available and works end-to-end; exports include version metadata.\n\n4. Filtering & Sorting\n   - Filter by project and completion state (all/active/completed).\n   - Sort by createdAt, dueDate, or manual order (position). Reordering persists and handles rebalances.\n\n5. Concurrency & multi-tab\n   - Cross-tab updates propagate within seconds via BroadcastChannel or storage events; UI reflects changes in other tabs.\n\n6. Offline & static asset behavior\n   - Data operations work offline (no network needed).\n   - After first load, the optional service worker ensures the app can load offline (if SW enabled). Update behavior is safe and user-visible.\n\n7. Security & privacy\n   - All user text is rendered as escaped plain text; XSS injection tests must pass.\n   - CSP and hosting guidance are provided in deploy docs.\n   - Optional local encryption is available and documented (opt-in).\n   - Dependency scanning and CI security checks configured.\n\n8. Reliability & data integrity\n   - DB migrations are implemented and tested.\n   - Project deletion handled atomically with tasks; rollback or undo available for destructive operations.\n   - Optimistic update rollback tested.\n\n9. Performance & scalability\n   - App remains responsive with datasets up to 5k tasks when using virtualization.\n   - Production bundle size targets enforced.\n\n10. Testing & CI\n   - CI runs lint, unit tests, security audit, bundle-size checks, and E2E before merging to main/deploy.\n   - Testing matrix covers Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit for persistence and IndexedDB behavior.\n\n11. Documentation\n   - README covers setup, build, test, deploy, backup/import/export instructions, privacy caveats, and optional encryption usage.\n   - In-app Settings includes “Export data”, “Import data”, “About storage” notes, and an indication about browser sync/backups.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Constraints\n\n- No server-side code for MVP.\n- No sign-in or third-party cloud sync in MVP.\n- Minimal dependencies: prefer few, small libraries; avoid including icon-heavy packages or UI frameworks that bloat bundle.\n- TypeScript for all source code; zod for runtime validation.\n- Keep production JS bundle under configured CI threshold (target < 1 MB).\n- Avoid use of innerHTML or other direct DOM injections.\n- Use UTC-normalized ISO timestamps for storage; display with locale-aware formatting in UI.\n- Storage fallback to localStorage only as last resort and with explicit user warning.\n- Use BroadcastChannel for cross-tab sync (fallback storage events).\n- Undo semantics:\n  - For task delete: soft-delete immediately in UI with toast Undo (e.g., 6–10 seconds); physical deletion after undo window or when user confirms.\n  - For project delete: require explicit confirmation dialog; default to unassign tasks and provide Undo.\n- Secrets: never store passwords or secrets in the repository or client-side storage. Deploy secrets must be in CI secret storage.\n- Accessibility:\n  - Use ARIA roles for dialogs and live regions for toasts.\n  - Ensure keyboard navigation for add/edit/toggle/delete operations.\n  - Automated axe checks in CI for main screens.\n- Testing constraints:\n  - Use fake-indexeddb in Node unit tests.\n  - E2E tests must run on Playwright test matrix (Chromium, Firefox, WebKit).\n  - Include tests for migration, import/export, multi-tab sync, quota handling, and XSS escapes.\n\n---\n\nThis specification resolves conflicts and hardens the original plan to produce a secure, reliable, maintainable, and developer-friendly MVP. It preserves the core product simplicity while closing critical gaps (data export/backup, storage failure handling, migrations, cross-tab sync, deletion semantics, and XSS/validation mitigations) identified by Architecture, Security, and QA reviews.\n\nNext steps (implementation checklist):\n- Implement Storage Adapter with robust IndexedDB open + onupgradeneeded migrations and typed error classes.\n- Implement TaskService & ProjectService with zod validation, optimistic update/rollback, and cross-tab emission.\n- Build UI components with accessibility and Undo flows, and integrate Export/Import UI.\n- Add BroadcastChannel wrapper and multi-tab tests.\n- Configure CI: lint, unit tests, security scan, bundle-size check, Playwright matrix, deploy step with secrets.\n- Document README + in-app Settings with export/import and privacy guidance."